==In other fields==
The zero of the [[Celsius]] temperature scale is (to the nearest whole number) 273 [[kelvin]]s. Thus, [[absolute zero]] (0 K) is approximately −273&nbsp;°C.<ref>{{citation|title=An Introduction to Physical Science|author1=James Shipman |author2=Jerry Wilson |author3=Charles Higgins |edition=13th|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2012|isbn=9781133104094|page=107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dxoM93eNPVEC&pg=PA107}}.</ref> The freezing temperature of water and the thermodynamic temperature of the [[triple point of water]] are both approximately 0&nbsp;°C or 273 K.<ref>{{citation|title=Physics: A World View|author1=Larry Kirkpatrick |author2=Gregory Francis |edition=6th|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2006|isbn=9780495010883|page=219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8hOLs-bmiYYC&pg=PA219}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Physics for Engineering|author1=Alphonso Hendricks |author2=Loganathan Subramony |author3=Charmaine Van Blerk |publisher=Juta and Company Ltd|year=1999|isbn=9780702144080|page=229|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8Kp-UwV4o0gC&pg=PA229}}.</ref>

