'''501''' ('''five hundred [and] one''') is the [[natural number]] following [[500 (number)|500]] and preceding [[502 (number)|502]].

501 is the sum of the first eighteen [[prime number|primes]].<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A007504|name=Sum of first n primes}}</ref>
There are 501 degree-8 [[polynomial]]s with integer coefficients, all of whose roots are in the unit disk.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber= A051894 |name=Number of monic polynomials with integer coefficients of degree n with all roots in unit disc}}</ref>
There are 501 ways of partitioning the digits from 0 to 9 into two sets, each of which contains at least two digits,<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber= A000247 |name=2^n-n-2}}</ref> and 501 ways of partitioning a set of five elements into any number of ordered sequences.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber= A000262|name=Number of "sets of lists": number of partitions of {1,..,n} into any number of lists, where a list means an ordered subset}}</ref>
501 is also a [[figurate number]] based on the [[5-orthoplex]] or 5-dimensional [[cross polytope]].<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A069038|name=G.f.: x*(1+x)^4/(1-x)^6}}</ref>

In the [[gematria]] of [[Eleazar of Worms]], the Hebrew words "temunah" (image) and "parsuf 'adam" (human face) both had the [[numerology|numerological]] value of 501. Eleazar used this equivalence to argue that, in several Biblical passages, God appeared to His prophets in the form of a human face.<ref>{{citation|title=Through a Speculum That Shines: Vision and Imagination in Medieval Jewish Mysticism|first=Elliot R.|last=Wolfson|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-691-01722-8|page=222|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FqKT7ML2re8C&pg=PA222}}.</ref>

